Task.Name: Read the note for an explanation of the purpose of this template
Task.Notes:
This template provides an approach for identifying, planning, and rolling out infrastructure improvements. The general subject chosen is "Security Infrastructure" because security involves a balance between the need for security and maintaining the ability to do business. However, this approach can be used to on many infrastructure initiatives.
A note on the resourcing of this plan: We have intentionally left the resources out of this plan, as depending on the infrastructure initiative, it is used in conjunction with the resource types will change as well. We felt it would not be helpful to place "IT Staff" on every activity.

Task.Name: Perform Needs Assessment
Task.Notes:
Needs Assessment is done from the point of view of: 1) Raw security needs 2) Business impact
Both of these must be kept in mind at all times. It makes no sense to spend a large amount of money implementing rigid security that severely hinders your people's abilities to get things done (and produce revenue). A balance must be achieved, depending on your joint requirements

Task.Name: Perform IT-centric need assessment
Task.Notes:
This is a raw security requirements collection effort Answer questions such as: What security levels do my clients require of me? What information sets do I have? How sensitive to the company are they? Who are the users of the information? How complex is the security model I must implement given user access requirements and information sensitivity levels.
Security considerations are (at a high level): authentication, encryption, access, integrity, and privacy.
These break down further into a core set of issues and actions that must be considered: disabling resources, managing content, isolating data, resources or access, software updating and security, staff roles, change and configuration management, intrusion detection and vulnerability analysis.

Task.Name: Perform business need assessment
Task.Notes: Here we identify the business needs driving the security requirements. However, we also identify performance, usage, and deployment timeframe requirements. These will all be reconciled in the next activity.

Task.Name: Reconcile IT-centric need with business requirements
Task.Notes: Here we reconcile the security needs with the business survival requirements. We could implement a huge amount of security but if the business fails because the security implemented cannot be used effectively then the security effort was useless.

Task.Name: Document reconciled requirements and time frame
Assess how well technology integrates with current infrastructure
Task.Notes: For example: Is this technology an easy upgrade to existing systems, or does it require a wholesale replacement of large portions of infrastructure?

Task.Name: Assess how well technology fits with current corporate strategies
Task.Notes: Corporate strategy can influence many things, for example: If corporate strategy is to de-centralize data centers or aggregate into data centers will this technology support that? If corporate strategy is to outsource the maintenance of this technology, then we need to ensure that there are sufficient metrics provided by the technology/components to allow us to define rigorous Service Level Agreements (SLAs) and provide for easy identification of when performance is becoming an issue so SLAs, including performance cannot be disputed because of questionable root cause.

Task.Name: Assess technology maintenance complexity
Task.Notes: Does this technology require mothering, or is it stable and reliable? Is this technology repaired at component, card, or unit level? What are the sparing needs considering criticality and Mean Time Between Failure? Does the technology or component provide for proactive monitoring and early indications of stress? Can the technology or component be easily tied into system monitoring tools?

Task.Name: Assess technology flexibility
Task.Notes: How well will this technology support changing requirements and direction, etc.?

Task.Name: Assess risks associated with this technology
Task.Notes: Identify risks associated with this specific technology (or technology component), for example: Is it well-understood or is it bleeding edge? Is it based on a "not-yet" standard, a recent standard that is not widely adopted or a proven standard? Is this technology provided by multiple companies? If not, how stable is the provider? If this is a new technology, how quickly are issues (once found) dealt with?

Task.Name: Assess skill-set required for this technology
Task.Notes: Do we have this skill in-house? How easy is it to find? How easy is it to develop? How expensive is it to find or develop?

Task.Name: Assess the price-points or value provided by this technology
Task.Notes: For example: If we are comparing long term storage technologies, what is the cost per gigabyte of storage? How frequently must the storage be 'refreshed' or 'rewritten' if the storage material decays over time?

Task.Name: Assess the time required to implement this technology into a solution
Task.Notes: Some technologies can be implemented rapidly and are more suitable for short term crisis management.

Task.Name: Time Bound "Technology" Research
Task.Notes:
It is very important to limit the amount of time spent analyzing technology. Technology is changing so fast that this activity could be never-ending, so you should set a reasonable limit for technology investigation. This limit is usually set by corporate need. If the corporation is heading toward a major performance crisis (in a year) because of the current infrastructure, technology and solution research must end early enough for solution development, testing, and deployment to be complete before the crisis point is reached.
The intent of this milestone is to provide the endpoint of this section of research. Set it appropriately.

Task.Name: Solution possibilities (combinations of technologies)
Task.Notes:
Although the different technologies are being researched and better understood, we will begin to build full solution possibilities out of multiple technologies. These solution possibilities can be considered as deployed in technology stages. While the solution is being defined, the usefulness of staging and the sequence of staging will be an added consideration in terms of comparing "solutions."
Note: Developing solutions begins as soon as you begin looking at technologies. Solutions are not fully formed for some time, but architects immediately begin thinking in terms of solutions.

Task.Name: Assess how well solutions integrate with current infrastructure
Assess how well solutions fit with current corporate strategies
Assess skill-set required for each solution
Assess the price-points or value provided each solution
Assess the time required to implement each solution
Assess solution staging and technology deployment roadmaps
Task.Notes: See notes on "solution possibilities."

Task.Name: Time Bound "Solution Development"
Task.Notes:
It is very important to limit the amount of time spent architecting solutions. Technology is changing so fast that this activity could be never-ending, so you should set a reasonable limit for solution development. This limit is usually set by corporate need. If the corporation is heading toward a major performance crisis (in a year) because of the current infrastructure, technology and solution research must end early enough for solution development, testing, and deployment to be complete before the crisis point is reached.
The intent of this milestone is to provide the endpoint of this section of research. Set it appropriately.

Task.Name: Solution comparison and selection
Task.Notes:
This stage is typically fast because all of the effort prior has acquainted the company well with the pros and cons of each solution.
The use of "time-bound" milestones can turn out to not be necessary, because a specific solution stands out early on and can become the obvious de facto winner.

Task.Name: Prepare the solution development and deployment schedule
Task.Notes: This can include internally handling or outsourcing of any or all of many areas: architecture, prototyping, scalability testing, maintenance planning and sparing, help desk, etc.

Task.Name: Prepare the solution training, support, and maintenance plans
Migration to solution
Task.Notes: The way production migrates to the deployed solution can happen in many different ways. Generally, either a staged approach type or a cutover type is planned. Testing and validation can change, depending on which method is chosen.
